compensation, the destruction of livelihoods), and secretive, inequitable wealth sharing.The Thein Sein administration has dealt with these conflicts by suspending projects; establishing an inquiry commission and an implementation committee; re-negotiating contracts and preparing to become a member of the Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative (EITI). These unprecedented measures will likely take place on an ad hoc basis rather than across the extractive industry. Dramatic changes to contracts are more likely to take place with Chinese (and other) corporations that are involved in large-scale rather than small-scale projects.The changing political circumstances - Myanmar no longer being reliant on a handful of countries for strategic and financial support and the necessity of taking into account the wishes of its electorate means that the political landscape has shifted under the feet of stakeholders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChina—Foreign economic relations—Myanmar. 0aEnergy Industries. 0aInvestments, Chinese—Myanmar. 0aInvestments, Foreign—Myanmar. 0aMyanmar—Foreign economic relations—China. 0aMyanmar—Politics and government. 4aEnergy Industries. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Energy.2bisacsh1 aPhilip, Andrews-Speed, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066300608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060667608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070099240uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981469533640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814695336423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/cov